00:14:38.876 --> 00:14:42.496
instead of just palliating, which some of the other treatments were used

245
00:14:42.536 --> 00:14:46.416
for. The other thing is that compassionate use programs have allowed

246
00:14:46.516 --> 00:14:50.296
us to look at things like alpha emitters in patients who have had no

247
00:14:50.476 --> 00:14:54.416
options, and we've really kind of seen the benefit of what they

248
00:14:54.476 --> 00:14:58.276
can do for these patients. And this has really driven a lot of research

249
00:14:58.336 --> 00:15:02.026
into this. The challenge is that these new novel isotopes,

250
00:15:02.116 --> 00:15:05.596
particularly the alpha emitters, the alpha emitters have traditionally been

251
00:15:05.636 --> 00:15:09.276
harvested from waste that we developed back when we were developing the

252
00:15:09.316 --> 00:15:12.885
Manhattan Project. And a lot of that waste is now gone.

253
00:15:13.356 --> 00:15:16.986
So we've had to come up with new ways to actually produce those isotopes,

254
00:15:17.376 --> 00:15:20.456
and it's not a trivial process. And so

255
00:15:20.996 --> 00:15:24.856
there's targets that we use that emit gases

256
00:15:24.896 --> 00:15:28.136
that we have to worry about. Radium-226 is not readily

257
00:15:28.176 --> 00:15:30.526
available. There's waste issues.

258
00:15:30.596 --> 00:15:34.156
There's just a number of things that we've had to address to really

259
00:15:34.216 --> 00:15:37.686
make these viable. That being said, there's

260
00:15:37.716 --> 00:15:41.216
now a lot of industry that's very interested in making this.

261
00:15:41.246 --> 00:15:45.206
And now what we're seeing is industry is coming on board with

262
00:15:45.256 --> 00:15:49.056
new ways to produce these and actually bringing these in

263
00:15:49.096 --> 00:15:52.736
using things like rotatrons and things like that to make them more readily

264
00:15:52.795 --> 00:15:56.716
available. So in the future, we're hoping to see that we'll have a

265
00:15:56.776 --> 00:15:59.616
more sustainable supply that will actually meet the demand.

266
00:16:01.416 --> 00:16:05.086
So as we're going through this, some of the challenges that we're

267
00:16:05.176 --> 00:16:08.836
having is we have a large number of early-stage projects.

268
00:16:08.876 --> 00:16:12.736
If you saw the slide that Kevin showed earlier, you see all

269
00:16:12.756 --> 00:16:15.276
these new agents that are going into the pipeline.

270
00:16:15.706 --> 00:16:19.636
And many of these are by large pharma or small companies who are very

271
00:16:19.776 --> 00:16:21.816
new to the field of radiopharmaceutical.

272
00:16:22.396 --> 00:16:26.296
And we need to make sure that we educate them about what

273
00:16:26.316 --> 00:16:28.276
is needed as we actually go through this.

274
00:16:28.816 --> 00:16:32.476
So it's very promising in that a lot of money is being spent and we have great

275
00:16:32.636 --> 00:16:35.416
opportunities, but we also have to look at some of the

276
00:16:35.436 --> 00:16:39.366
limitations. So some of that is that we need to make sure that we have

277
00:16:39.416 --> 00:16:43.016
enough of the therapeutic radionuclides for the manufacturing supply.

278
00:16:43.606 --> 00:16:47.376
And so keep in mind, when we're doing therapy, we're using 10 to

279
00:16:47.576 --> 00:16:51.396
20 times more of the isotope, and we're normally delivering at four to six

280
00:16:51.436 --> 00:16:54.496
times. So that's a huge amount that we need to make.

281
00:16:55.036 --> 00:16:58.816
And these agents now have additional challenges that we

282
00:16:58.876 --> 00:17:02.496
need to go through when we're thinking about how to handle them in the clinic,

283
00:17:02.926 --> 00:17:06.916
the chemistry when you have that much radioactivity, and then the pharmacy

284
00:17:06.956 --> 00:17:09.466
expertise to actually bring them forward.

285
00:17:09.477 --> 00:17:12.876
And what we're seeing is that we're seeing that this is new to the

286
00:17:12.977 --> 00:17:16.916
FDA. And so we're having to work with them to understand these new

287
00:17:16.977 --> 00:17:20.076
isotopes and what the regulations are that we're putting in

288
00:17:20.176 --> 00:17:23.616
place. And we're working with the USP to try to develop new

289
00:17:23.656 --> 00:17:26.856
chapters. So there's a lot we need to do to make

290
00:17:26.916 --> 00:17:30.836
sure that as we see different production and

291
00:17:30.906 --> 00:17:34.756
manufacturing come online, that we put in regulations that can

292
00:17:34.816 --> 00:17:38.476
actually accommodate both for industry and academia as

293
00:17:38.516 --> 00:17:40.896
well as industry as we move

294
00:17:40.976 --> 00:17:44.832
forward.Now, as we look at this, this is

295
00:17:45.672 --> 00:17:49.112
from a paper that came out from "The Lancet" Commission on

296
00:17:49.152 --> 00:17:53.112
theranostics. And just to kind of show you, this paper kind of went

297
00:17:53.182 --> 00:17:57.132
through and it listed various radionuclides and what they could be used for and

298
00:17:57.212 --> 00:17:58.811
how you could actually produce them.

299
00:17:59.292 --> 00:18:03.052
And it also showed the location of

300
00:18:03.092 --> 00:18:06.832
reactors throughout the world. And where you want to be is really in that dark

301
00:18:06.912 --> 00:18:10.212
green area on the map, because that's where they have the most reactors.

302
00:18:10.772 --> 00:18:14.612
And you can see in the US, where we use 50% of

303
00:18:14.692 --> 00:18:17.952
all the radionuclides, we really have the lowest number of

304
00:18:17.992 --> 00:18:21.592
reactors in the world. And this is what really creates the

305
00:18:21.652 --> 00:18:24.552
challenge and why we're bringing so many things actually in.

306
00:18:25.052 --> 00:18:28.342
And what you can see is that Europe is in a pretty good place, but Asia in

307
00:18:28.412 --> 00:18:32.192
particularly, has a large number of reactors, and they're bringing on

308
00:18:32.492 --> 00:18:33.072
many new.

309
00:18:34.192 --> 00:18:36.852
Now if you look at cyclotrons, which is the other way we make

310
00:18:38.132 --> 00:18:41.512
radioisotopes, you can see we're in a bit better place there.

311
00:18:42.152 --> 00:18:45.352
We're green. We're not dark green, but at least we're in the green

312
00:18:45.392 --> 00:18:49.212
here. And again, you can see that Europe is doing really well.

313
00:18:49.392 --> 00:18:53.362
But again, you see that Asia really has predominant

314
00:18:53.432 --> 00:18:57.202
infrastructure in this area. And this is one reason why Asia is really

315
00:18:57.212 --> 00:19:00.452
predicted to really grow as we move forward.

316
00:19:01.012 --> 00:19:04.952
But we really need the infrastructure to basically produce these

317
00:19:05.032 --> 00:19:08.962
isotopes. So when we're looking at isotopes and

318
00:19:08.992 --> 00:19:12.972
which ones we want to use, we need to look at the mode of decay,

319
00:19:13.272 --> 00:19:13.952
so what

320
00:19:14.892 --> 00:19:18.472
is given off by the decay, the half-life, because we want the

321
00:19:18.512 --> 00:19:22.172
half-life to match the biological half-life of the agent.

322
00:19:22.752 --> 00:19:26.382
We want it to be very pure and to have a good specific activity.

323
00:19:26.932 --> 00:19:28.872
It's important for it to be available.

324
00:19:28.912 --> 00:19:32.192
There are many isotopes that would be great to use, but we can't make it in

325
00:19:32.232 --> 00:19:35.582
significant quantities, so there's really no point in going down

326
00:19:35.632 --> 00:19:39.532
there. And then we need it to have high quality, and we

327
00:19:39.592 --> 00:19:41.372
want it to be at a reasonable cost.

328
00:19:42.272 --> 00:19:46.112
And then for radiolabeling, we like it to be simple, it needs to

329
00:19:46.152 --> 00:19:49.552
be stable, and we want it to have ideal pharmacokinetics.

330
00:19:49.592 --> 00:19:52.932
So ideally, it would go to the tumor, and anything that doesn't is going to clear

331
00:19:53.012 --> 00:19:53.892
out very quickly.

332
00:19:55.432 --> 00:19:59.152
So most of the types of things that we're looking at for

333
00:19:59.332 --> 00:20:01.212
therapy, we want things that emit particles.

334
00:20:01.332 --> 00:20:03.212
So we're looking at alpha particles,

335
00:20:04.292 --> 00:20:07.992
beta particles, which are electrons, and for imaging, we're looking at

336
00:20:08.092 --> 00:20:11.692
positrons, which annihilate to give off the two 511 KeVs.

337
00:20:12.232 --> 00:20:15.412
And then for SPECT, we want basically a photon that is emitted.

338
00:20:16.632 --> 00:20:20.602
Now, for diagnosis, the ideal is that we want to image, and particularly in

339
00:20:20.612 --> 00:20:23.992
theranostics, we're trying to determine if the target is there.

340
00:20:24.562 --> 00:20:28.481
And if we have enough of the agent taken up at the target that we can actually

341
00:20:28.512 --> 00:20:32.322
go forward and do therapy. And we want to use it for dosimetry,

342
00:20:32.512 --> 00:20:35.692
which I understand was talked about earlier, and then we want to use it to

343
00:20:35.732 --> 00:20:39.541
understand the pharmacokinetics, particularly as we move forward in clinical

344
00:20:39.632 --> 00:20:43.232
trials to inform the doses and to inform that that

345
00:20:43.292 --> 00:20:47.232
patient is still moving as we go forward, and we want it to have such

346
00:20:47.312 --> 00:20:50.012
an emission that it actually external from the body.

347
00:20:50.972 --> 00:20:53.232
For therapy, we want to use particle emitters.

348
00:20:53.652 --> 00:20:57.212
Most prominently has been used is beta particles, and

349
00:20:57.252 --> 00:21:00.112
that's due to the fact that they're the ones largely produced.

350
00:21:00.532 --> 00:21:03.912
But there's been a lot of work looking at alpha particles and Auger

351
00:21:03.952 --> 00:21:04.672
electrons.

352
00:21:07.052 --> 00:21:10.832
So the one thing we need to really look at

353
00:21:10.912 --> 00:21:14.742
is making sure that we match the half-life to the uptake and the

354
00:21:14.792 --> 00:21:18.592
clearance of the agent. And I had a talk one time

355
00:21:18.652 --> 00:21:21.712
with a university talking about different radionuclides.

356
00:21:22.332 --> 00:21:26.072
And the person basically said to me, "Well, I can use carbon-11 for

357
00:21:26.112 --> 00:21:30.092
everything." And I was like, "Well, actually you can't, because if

358
00:21:30.132 --> 00:21:33.972
you're using an antibody that's going to take a long time to be taken up, the

359
00:21:34.012 --> 00:21:37.852
amount of carbon-11 you would have to inject into that patient would be

360
00:21:37.912 --> 00:21:41.872
quite toxic." So you really need something that has a long half-life that's

361
00:21:41.892 --> 00:21:44.332
going to allow you to get there to actually use it.

362
00:21:44.862 --> 00:21:48.432
And then most of the time we're making these, and we have to ship them somewhere

363
00:21:48.472 --> 00:21:52.412
else, particularly for therapy. So it needs to have a long enough half-life

364
00:21:52.472 --> 00:21:54.332
so we can actually do that transport.

365
00:21:55.232 --> 00:21:59.052
The specific activity, we usually want it to be high, but we have

366
00:21:59.132 --> 00:22:03.032
seen cases where if it's too high, then we see a lot of normal tissue

367
00:22:03.112 --> 00:22:05.512
uptake. So we have to make sure that

368
00:22:07.252 --> 00:22:11.162
it matches what we need for that agent, and we have to look at what the production

369
00:22:11.192 --> 00:22:13.242
and how we actually make that target material.

370
00:22:14.692 --> 00:22:18.092
The chemistry, we'd like it to be fairly easy and straightforward.

371
00:22:18.312 --> 00:22:21.732
I actually started out as a technetium rhenium chemistry, and

372
00:22:21.812 --> 00:22:25.432
technetium and rhenium have a lot of different oxidation states, and so it's very

373
00:22:25.472 --> 00:22:29.412
difficult to get one agent. You can get a lot, but it takes a lot of work

374
00:22:29.452 --> 00:22:32.932
to optimize it. So there's been a lot of work-- Let me see. Can I go back?

375
00:22:33.992 --> 00:22:37.472
Really looking at trying to use radiometals where you can just do a simple

376
00:22:37.572 --> 00:22:40.392
complex through a chelate and get a simple agent.

377
00:22:40.932 --> 00:22:44.732
But then you also have to worry about the in vivo clearance of these

378
00:22:44.772 --> 00:22:48.692
agents. And one of the nice things about rhenium-186

379
00:22:48.832 --> 00:22:52.252
is that if it goes to normal targets, it actually gets

380
00:22:52.332 --> 00:22:56.032
oxidized up to prenate, which then washes out very quickly from the

381
00:22:56.072 --> 00:22:58.712
kidney. So it really lowers that normal

382
00:23:00.172 --> 00:23:03.592
organ uptake. But the chemistry also affects the

383
00:23:03.632 --> 00:23:07.492
separation and purification. And sometimes, like for instance,

384
00:23:07.532 --> 00:23:10.472
we're making actinium-225 through distillation.

385
00:23:10.512 --> 00:23:14.252
We have to separate that from four other isotopes, which can be

386
00:23:14.492 --> 00:23:15.792
rather complicated to do.

387
00:23:17.592 --> 00:23:21.212
Now, the other thing you want to look at is the range that these particles actually

388
00:23:21.272 --> 00:23:25.182
travel. And so the big circle here, what you're seeing is this is kind

389
00:23:25.212 --> 00:23:28.112
of a demonstration of a range of a beta particle.

390
00:23:28.132 --> 00:23:30.642
And beta particles can travel long ranges.

391
00:23:30.672 --> 00:23:34.062
And for large tumors, this can be fairly ideal because you can get the

392
00:23:34.132 --> 00:23:36.812
crossfire, and you don't necessarily have to target every tumor.

393
00:23:37.352 --> 00:23:40.972
But if you're looking at small metastases, what can happen is that beta particle

394
00:23:41.072 --> 00:23:44.652
can leave that small metastasis, and the dose is going to go to that

395
00:23:44.692 --> 00:23:48.472
normal tissue. And that normal tissue toxicity is then going to

396
00:23:48.532 --> 00:23:52.392
lower the amount of activity that you can deliver, which is going to lower the

397
00:23:52.432 --> 00:23:56.262
overall efficacy of that drug. So you can look at other things

398
00:23:56.262 --> 00:24:00.132
such as alpha particles, which are shown in the red on here,

399
00:24:00.152 --> 00:24:03.956
and you can see that this travels a very short distance.So all of the

400
00:24:03.976 --> 00:24:07.356
dose then gets retained into that small metastasis,

401
00:24:08.076 --> 00:24:11.476
and you're going to see very minimal toxicity to normal tissues.

402
00:24:12.096 --> 00:24:16.016
And we also see this for conversion electrons, which is actually shown in the

403
00:24:16.056 --> 00:24:19.696
yellow. So the range gets really important in actually

404
00:24:19.756 --> 00:24:23.636
choosing the radionuclide for the disease that you're looking at.

405
00:24:24.716 --> 00:24:28.456
Now, most time for radionuclides, they don't necessarily go where we want

406
00:24:28.496 --> 00:24:32.416
to just by injection. There are some that are iodine-131,

407
00:24:32.516 --> 00:24:36.416
strontium-89, but many others we have to come up with, quote, "a

408
00:24:36.476 --> 00:24:39.856
mechanism of delivery." How do we keep it where we want it to

409
00:24:39.896 --> 00:24:43.736
go? And so some of these we use like seeds or particles, and this is

410
00:24:43.816 --> 00:24:46.756
used particularly for treating prostate cancer.

411
00:24:47.376 --> 00:24:50.716
We use chemistry to actually develop small molecules to give them

412
00:24:50.756 --> 00:24:54.696
properties. For instance, we use phosphonate compounds to get agents to

413
00:24:54.736 --> 00:24:58.556
go to bone cancer for palliation, or we can use molecular

414
00:24:58.616 --> 00:25:02.476
targeting agents. So we have agents that target receptors that

415
00:25:02.496 --> 00:25:06.416
are overexpressed, and we can attach the radionuclide, and it kind

416
00:25:06.456 --> 00:25:10.176
of behaves kind of as a taxi cab and takes it to the agent.

417
00:25:10.756 --> 00:25:14.136
And there's been a lot of interest in actually using nanoparticles because we can

418
00:25:14.196 --> 00:25:17.936
tend to increase the dose and use the ER effect to get these

419
00:25:17.996 --> 00:25:18.636
taken in.

420
00:25:20.596 --> 00:25:24.126
So for the targeted approach, which is the largest that has been used for

421
00:25:24.176 --> 00:25:27.556
theranostics, you have a targeting vector, normally a

422
00:25:27.596 --> 00:25:30.456
peptide, a monoclonal antibody, or a hormone.

423
00:25:31.006 --> 00:25:34.956
And to that, you attach your radiometal through what's called a bifunctional

424
00:25:35.036 --> 00:25:38.816
chelating agent. And this is normally an agent that stably binds

425
00:25:38.876 --> 00:25:42.716
that metal to go in vivo. You then have a

426
00:25:42.776 --> 00:25:46.356
linker that attaches the bifunctional chelator to the

427
00:25:46.436 --> 00:25:50.396
targeting vector. And that linker can become very important because

428
00:25:50.496 --> 00:25:54.396
it needs to ensure that that metal bifunctional chelator does

429
00:25:54.436 --> 00:25:58.116
not interfere with the affinity of your targeting vector.

430
00:25:58.576 --> 00:26:02.536
But you can also modify that to modify some of the pharmacodynamics of

431
00:26:02.576 --> 00:26:04.536
what's going on in vivo.

432
00:26:06.676 --> 00:26:10.056
So here's just a list of some of the common

433
00:26:10.256 --> 00:26:14.216
therapeutic isotopes that I've been looking at and also some of the new ones that

434
00:26:14.226 --> 00:26:17.216
are coming up. Iodine-131. We have

435
00:26:17.336 --> 00:26:20.586
iodine-124 and 123 that we can use for imaging.

436
00:26:21.416 --> 00:26:25.096
And then yttrium-90. And when I started in the field, it was thought that you could

437
00:26:25.116 --> 00:26:27.896
do everything with iodine-131 and yttrium-90.

438
00:26:28.556 --> 00:26:31.866
And then they started doing trials with yttrium-90, and what they found is some of

439
00:26:31.896 --> 00:26:35.856
the normal tissue toxicity was too high, so they needed to look for other agents.

440
00:26:36.556 --> 00:26:40.456
And so that's when we started looking at lutetium-177 because it had a

441
00:26:40.536 --> 00:26:44.506
lower range beta particle, and that lowered particularly the overall

442
00:26:44.596 --> 00:26:48.376
kidney toxicity. But these are plus three metals, and there are many

443
00:26:48.416 --> 00:26:51.836
plus three imaging agents that we can actually use to image these.

444
00:26:52.336 --> 00:26:53.956
And then you have rhenium-technetium.

445
00:26:54.136 --> 00:26:57.716
There's bromine, which there's a lot of work, and then the copper isotopes,

446
00:26:57.816 --> 00:27:01.116
copper-67 for therapy, and then copper-64 for imaging.

447
00:27:02.656 --> 00:27:06.496
And then here are some of the novel ones that are coming up that people are looking

448
00:27:06.556 --> 00:27:09.976
at. Scandium-47, which has properties similar to lutetium,

449
00:27:10.676 --> 00:27:13.936
and then scandium-44 and 43, which can be made on a

450
00:27:13.976 --> 00:27:17.816
cyclotron. Actinium-225, which is an alpha emitter,

451
00:27:18.376 --> 00:27:20.956
and then there are a number of different imaging agents for that.

452
00:27:21.416 --> 00:27:25.256
Arsenic-77 is a longer-lived isotope which has

453
00:27:25.296 --> 00:27:27.096
been used for antibodies.

454
00:27:27.816 --> 00:27:31.716
Terbium-161, which has conversion electrons and has been

455
00:27:31.776 --> 00:27:34.376
shown to deliver higher doses than lutetium.

456
00:27:35.016 --> 00:27:38.866
Thorium-227 and lead-212, which were both alpha emitters,

457
00:27:38.936 --> 00:27:40.356
which there's a lot of interest in.

458
00:27:41.896 --> 00:27:45.676
So when we're looking at these isotope pairs and we're trying to choose

459
00:27:45.716 --> 00:27:49.656
which ones we want to use, it's best if we have matched

460
00:27:49.696 --> 00:27:53.656
pairs. And if we don't have matched pairs, a challenge can be is that the

461
00:27:53.696 --> 00:27:57.616
chemistry can be different, and that chemistry can impact

462
00:27:57.676 --> 00:27:59.676
the overall uptake of those agents.

463
00:28:00.056 --> 00:28:02.036
And we can see differences in biology.

464
00:28:02.556 --> 00:28:06.276
So we can see differences in uptake in the tumor versus the

465
00:28:06.316 --> 00:28:09.996
normal tissue, and that can impact the choices that we

466
00:28:10.036 --> 00:28:12.616
make. We often see varying half-lives.

467
00:28:12.656 --> 00:28:16.426
The imaging surrogate normally has a shorter half-life, and the question is:

468
00:28:16.656 --> 00:28:20.655
Do you need it longer? For your pre-clinical trials, you might want to have a

469
00:28:20.696 --> 00:28:23.816
longer imaging agent so you can really understand what happens.

470
00:28:24.316 --> 00:28:26.536
So you need to kind of determine what you can have.

471
00:28:26.936 --> 00:28:30.536
And then it's important that it's available so that as you enter pre-clinical

472
00:28:30.596 --> 00:28:31.816
trials, it's actually there.

473
00:28:33.256 --> 00:28:34.216
Now, one of the

474
00:28:35.776 --> 00:28:39.356
standards that has really been used to compare a lot of different radionuclides

475
00:28:39.436 --> 00:28:43.076
is somatostatin. And so octreotide is a

476
00:28:43.136 --> 00:28:46.536
modified somatostatin analog. It was modified with D-amino

477
00:28:46.676 --> 00:28:49.336
acids because it had a really short half-life.

478
00:28:49.356 --> 00:28:53.036
It normally lasts about three minutes if you inject it in vivo.

479
00:28:53.436 --> 00:28:57.086
So by adding in the D-amino acids, this made it have a much longer

480
00:28:57.176 --> 00:28:57.776
half-life,

481
00:28:58.636 --> 00:29:02.416
and it has a very high affinity for somatostatin

482
00:29:02.736 --> 00:29:06.136
2 and actually somatostatin 5. So you can use those for

483
00:29:06.416 --> 00:29:08.476
imaging and treating neuroendocrine tumors.

484
00:29:09.176 --> 00:29:12.876
I was just at the TAP meeting, and people are now using it for doing breast cancer

485
00:29:12.956 --> 00:29:16.176
as well. But it was originally designed as a chemotherapeutic.

486
00:29:17.976 --> 00:29:20.916
So when we're using these peptides, what we need to do is to attach

487
00:29:20.996 --> 00:29:24.116
chelators to actually bind these radiometals.

488
00:29:24.286 --> 00:29:24.616
And these are

489
00:29:26.016 --> 00:29:27.016
not all-encompassing,

490
00:29:27.836 --> 00:29:30.316
but these are some common chelators that are used.

491
00:29:30.416 --> 00:29:34.346
EDTA and DTPA for indium-111, bismuth-213,

492
00:29:35.056 --> 00:29:38.856
and DOTA has been considered the all-encompassing chelator

493
00:29:38.936 --> 00:29:41.605
because you can bind a variety of different chelators.

494
00:29:42.036 --> 00:29:45.956
And then TETA was initially actually used

495
00:29:45.996 --> 00:29:46.516
for copper.

496
00:29:48.176 --> 00:29:52.056
So the somatostatin ligand, Helmut Macken attached a

497
00:29:52.076 --> 00:29:55.116
DOTA chelator because he wanted to basically use this for

498
00:29:55.136 --> 00:29:59.000
therapy.And what he did is he looked at a variety of plus

499
00:29:59.020 --> 00:30:02.600
three radiometals for doing both imaging and therapy.

500
00:30:03.260 --> 00:30:06.440
So he initially looked at yttrium-90, and then he looked at

501
00:30:06.540 --> 00:30:10.300
indium-111 and gallium-68 for really doing

502
00:30:10.380 --> 00:30:14.340
some of the imaging. And at the time, these are plus three metals, and it was

503
00:30:14.380 --> 00:30:17.300
basically felt that you weren't going to see any real difference.

504
00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:21.920
But it turned out that we saw major differences when we went in vivo.

505
00:30:22.460 --> 00:30:26.319
And so here the white is the indium DTPA

506
00:30:26.600 --> 00:30:29.340
TreaScan, which is quite different, but it's a different chelator.

507
00:30:29.900 --> 00:30:33.280
But when you look at the indium-111 DOTATOC and

508
00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:35.100
yttrium-90, they're fairly close.

509
00:30:35.740 --> 00:30:38.560
But when you look at the gallium-67, you see

510
00:30:39.820 --> 00:30:43.420
much higher uptake in the tumor, and it also turned out you had much

511
00:30:43.720 --> 00:30:45.340
more clearance in normal tissues.

512
00:30:45.920 --> 00:30:49.900
And this is because the gallium is a six coordinate compound and has an extra

513
00:30:49.960 --> 00:30:53.910
negative charge, and this extra negative charge is what's causing the higher

514
00:30:53.980 --> 00:30:57.960
uptake. So if you're looking at this to try to understand the uptake of

515
00:30:58.020 --> 00:31:01.940
yttrium-90, you have to be very careful because it's going to overestimate

516
00:31:01.980 --> 00:31:05.720
what goes to the tumor and kind of underestimate what goes to the normal

517
00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:06.280
tissues.

518
00:31:08.140 --> 00:31:11.340
Here you can see an image of the indium DTPA and the

519
00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:15.000
gallium-68, and you can see the gallium-68 is a PET

520
00:31:15.100 --> 00:31:18.780
emitter, a positron emitter, and you can see that you have much higher

521
00:31:18.860 --> 00:31:22.800
resolution, and this is what really led to this being approved and

522
00:31:23.120 --> 00:31:24.500
being commonly used today.

523
00:31:25.780 --> 00:31:28.980
Now, there was a lot of interest in using copper-64.

524
00:31:29.540 --> 00:31:33.170
Some of the challenges with copper-64 and copper-67 was really their

525
00:31:33.200 --> 00:31:36.880
initial production, which was via reactor and via high

526
00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:39.120
energy protons, and we just couldn't make enough.

527
00:31:39.580 --> 00:31:43.480
The DeNardos were trying to use copper-67 because it seemed fairly ideal for

528
00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:44.700
metastatic disease.

529
00:31:45.820 --> 00:31:49.530
But we've now got copper-64 that we can routinely produce in our

530
00:31:49.660 --> 00:31:53.390
cyclotrons, and copper-67 can be made by

531
00:31:53.420 --> 00:31:56.190
rotatrons, which through the photonuclear route.

532
00:31:56.900 --> 00:32:00.600
And the group in Australia used what are called Sargent's and ligands, and these

533
00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:04.120
are ligands that tightly bind the copper chelator.

534
00:32:04.130 --> 00:32:08.020
And what you can see here is that when you look at the copper-64, you

535
00:32:08.060 --> 00:32:11.860
have very high uptake in the tumor and you have fast

536
00:32:12.060 --> 00:32:16.040
clearance through the liver. If you use DOTA, it turns out that the copper

537
00:32:16.060 --> 00:32:18.120
is reduced, and you have uptake in the liver.

538
00:32:18.760 --> 00:32:22.650
If you look at the copper-67 compared to lutetium, you see that

539
00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:24.040
the uptake is very similar.

540
00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:28.620
Now, the nice thing about this is that you can use the copper-64 to image

541
00:32:28.700 --> 00:32:32.380
patients, determine that they're positive, that they have low uptake in normal

542
00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:36.260
tissues. You can then go on and use the copper-67, and the

543
00:32:36.320 --> 00:32:39.180
copper-67 has a spec photon that you can image.

544
00:32:39.640 --> 00:32:42.620
And here you can see that they actually line up very well.

545
00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:45.820
So this is really an ideal matched pair.

546
00:32:45.860 --> 00:32:49.580
There are other matched pairs. Lead-212 is an

547
00:32:49.700 --> 00:32:53.580
agent that decays giving off an alpha emitter, bismuth-212, and there's a

548
00:32:53.600 --> 00:32:55.080
lot of interest in using this.

549
00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:59.960
This is an agent that's being developed by Perspective, and it's

550
00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:02.120
an agent, again, for neuroendocrine tumors.

551
00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:06.600
And you can use lead-203, which can be made on a cyclotron for actually

552
00:33:06.640 --> 00:33:10.360
doing the SPECT imaging. And so this gives you a good ideal, and it's

553
00:33:10.420 --> 00:33:14.300
fairly great for doing preclinical trials or

554
00:33:14.340 --> 00:33:18.060
clinical trials. And here you can see some of the images that were done at one,

555
00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:19.540
four, and 18 hours.

556
00:33:20.840 --> 00:33:24.240
And then finally, scandium-47 and scandium-44.

557
00:33:24.700 --> 00:33:28.060
Scandium-47 is similar to lutetium, but it does have a

558
00:33:28.100 --> 00:33:31.320
photon that you can image that's very similar to

559
00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:34.940
technetium-99m, so ideal for SPECT cameras.

560
00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:38.930
And then scandium-44 is a short-lived positron emitter that

561
00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:41.940
can be made on cyclotrons but also via a generator.

562
00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:46.480
And this is some work that was actually done at PSI, in which they looked

563
00:33:46.580 --> 00:33:48.080
at, again, a

564
00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:51.440
somatostatin analog that targets.

565
00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:55.180
And here in A, you see the uptake of the

566
00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:58.780
SPECT, and in B, you see the positron emitter, and you can see that they

567
00:33:58.850 --> 00:34:00.010
match very well.

568
00:34:01.380 --> 00:34:04.960
So in conclusion, we've had a lot of research and development that is

569
00:34:05.040 --> 00:34:08.960
ongoing. We have a lot of new radionuclides, which

570
00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:12.400
help as we have these new agents and allow us to really do precision

571
00:34:13.640 --> 00:34:16.960
medicine. We have a lot of work that's ongoing, which is

572
00:34:17.440 --> 00:34:19.551
really offering patients the opportunity.

573
00:34:20.170 --> 00:34:24.100
Economically, radionuclides are now in a position where industry is

574
00:34:24.140 --> 00:34:28.080
stepping in and supplying them, which is getting us to the point that we

575
00:34:28.160 --> 00:34:31.020
can actually support the clinical trials and then hopefully

576
00:34:31.361 --> 00:34:33.781
further drug development in the future.

577
00:34:34.321 --> 00:34:35.700
And on that note, I thank you.

578
00:34:41.341 --> 00:34:42.380
Thanks so much, Cathy.

579
00:34:43.420 --> 00:34:47.060
We're just going to hold the questions until after the next talk as well as the

580
00:34:47.140 --> 00:34:50.540
online one. So if you're online and you're wondering why we're not asking, that's

581
00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:50.801
why.

582
00:34:54.920 --> 00:34:55.071
Great.

583
00:34:55.720 --> 00:34:57.480
So thanks, Cathy, for a great talk.

584
00:34:57.960 --> 00:35:01.700
I'm going to shift gears a little bit and look more at the application side.

585
00:35:01.710 --> 00:35:05.660
And in this talk, I'm going to focus on what we're using now in the

586
00:35:05.700 --> 00:35:09.560
clinic and agents and types

587
00:35:09.620 --> 00:35:12.780
of trials and treatments that are likely to be in the near future.

588
00:35:13.780 --> 00:35:16.500
I was expecting a disclosure slide to show.

589
00:35:16.540 --> 00:35:20.400
My disclosures are online, but the one that's really relevant to this talk is I do

590
00:35:20.440 --> 00:35:24.360
consulting and have some research support from Novartis, who makes two of the

591
00:35:24.380 --> 00:35:28.210
drugs, the dotatate and PSMA therapies I'll be talking about.

592
00:35:28.550 --> 00:35:31.720
I'll also be talking about some investigational agents that are not in routine

593
00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:35.689
clinical use, and I'll try to make it very clear when we're talking about things

594
00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:39.250
we do routinely, clinically, that are FDA approved and those that are

595
00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:43.060
investigational.So this is kind of a similar schematic to what

596
00:35:43.340 --> 00:35:46.740
Kathy showed. When I think of theranostics, I think about some sort of

597
00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:50.640
pharmacologically active portion that delivers the

598
00:35:50.650 --> 00:35:54.070
drug where you want it to go, maybe clears it from where you don't want it,

599
00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:58.440
linked to radioactivity. And really you do need to think of the

600
00:35:58.480 --> 00:36:02.360
entire radiopharmaceutical or radiotheranostic as

601
00:36:02.420 --> 00:36:06.240
a whole, because the chelator, the linker, or the

602
00:36:06.280 --> 00:36:10.240
metal can affect what you see. I'm agnostic

603
00:36:10.260 --> 00:36:13.860
to whether we should have a G in it. I like to say theranostic without the G.

604
00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:18.120
I think both are fine. Why are these exciting?

605
00:36:19.100 --> 00:36:22.720
Radiation has been a cornerstone of cancer therapy for a long time.

606
00:36:23.420 --> 00:36:27.040
And a lot of it's delivered externally, but by using radiopharmaceuticals, we

607
00:36:27.080 --> 00:36:30.980
can go after targets on the tumor cells

608
00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.020
themselves or in the microenvironment to more selectively

609
00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:39.860
give radiation therapy. Additionally, we can deliver it throughout the entire

610
00:36:39.880 --> 00:36:43.860
body, which is an advantage over external beam radiation

611
00:36:43.900 --> 00:36:46.880
therapy for people with metastatic disease.

612
00:36:47.260 --> 00:36:50.020
Additionally, the ability to image

613
00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:53.440
beforehand and see if the target's there in sufficient

614
00:36:53.520 --> 00:36:56.920
quantities before treating is something that's very important clinically,

615
00:36:57.440 --> 00:36:59.500
and it's also important for clinical trials.

616
00:36:59.580 --> 00:37:03.260
And I'm not going to discuss it much, but more and more companies and

617
00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:08.520
agent developers are using this property to decide which

618
00:37:08.840 --> 00:37:12.640
of a class of therapeutics, which molecule is most promising.

619
00:37:13.140 --> 00:37:17.000
And really importantly for imaging, we can look at the entire metastatic

620
00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:17.800
burden. We're not

621
00:37:19.100 --> 00:37:22.150
subject to some of the sampling errors that you can have with

622
00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:26.200
biopsy. And finally, like other drugs, we

623
00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:30.180
can be used in combination. And I think that's one of the areas where

624
00:37:30.200 --> 00:37:33.820
we're going to see a lot of growth is radiopharmaceuticals in conjunction and

625
00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:35.500
combination with other therapies.

626
00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:39.840
So I agree, somatostatin receptor ligands like dotatate are great

627
00:37:39.880 --> 00:37:43.740
examples. So here we have the targeting part of a somatostatin

628
00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:45.960
receptor ligand and the DOTA chelator.

629
00:37:46.320 --> 00:37:49.980
If we use gallium-68 or copper-64, we have nice PET

630
00:37:50.040 --> 00:37:51.040
imaging compounds.

631
00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.460
If we switch this out for lutetium or other radiometals with therapeutic

632
00:37:55.540 --> 00:37:59.340
properties, the same molecule is now a

633
00:37:59.380 --> 00:38:01.860
therapy. So I'm going to quick quiz.

634
00:38:01.960 --> 00:38:05.020
Patient one, patient two, both have metastatic neuroendocrine tumors.

635
00:38:05.100 --> 00:38:08.160
We're looking at their CTs, which one should get

636
00:38:08.820 --> 00:38:09.840
dotatate therapy?

637
00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:12.020
And you don't know the answer.

638
00:38:13.080 --> 00:38:17.060
We can see these metastases in the liver, but one of the

639
00:38:17.140 --> 00:38:20.360
concepts that I think is really changing in the era of theranostics is we're often

640
00:38:20.380 --> 00:38:23.750
doing imaging not to see whether a patient has cancer

641
00:38:23.820 --> 00:38:26.960
or stage it, although those remain very important.

642
00:38:26.980 --> 00:38:30.680
We're really doing this to biologically characterize the tumor to make treatment

643
00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:33.860
decisions. So those who guessed patient two were correct.

644
00:38:34.340 --> 00:38:37.860
Patient two has a lot of somatostatin receptor expression seen with

645
00:38:37.880 --> 00:38:41.220
dotatate PET, whereas there is some in patient one's

646
00:38:41.300 --> 00:38:45.100
metastases, but much lower with some mets really having

647
00:38:45.940 --> 00:38:49.680
barely higher uptake than liver. And if we look at these maximum

648
00:38:49.740 --> 00:38:53.660
intensity projection images, which allow us to look at the PET, and throughout the

649
00:38:53.700 --> 00:38:57.540
whole body, you can see in patient one, actually some of the retroperitoneal lymph

650
00:38:57.580 --> 00:39:01.360
nodes have a lot of somatostatin receptor expression, whereas the

651
00:39:01.380 --> 00:39:04.560
liver metastases don't, and this patient is treatment naive.

652
00:39:06.420 --> 00:39:10.000
So you would get a different answer in terms of the target density

653
00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:13.280
depending on where you biopsy this patient's cancer.

654
00:39:13.320 --> 00:39:16.920
Whereas patient two, at least for the macroscopic disease, has a uniform

655
00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:20.700
somatostatin receptor expression, and we can't necessarily predict

656
00:39:20.710 --> 00:39:23.980
whether they'll respond or not, but we know we will deliver high amounts of

657
00:39:24.020 --> 00:39:26.840
radiation to their tumor burden.

658
00:39:28.180 --> 00:39:30.860
Good discussion about beta and alpha emitters.

659
00:39:31.400 --> 00:39:35.060
Betas tend to cause single-strand breaks, and so you

660
00:39:35.080 --> 00:39:37.760
generally need higher activities to get effects.

661
00:39:39.300 --> 00:39:42.560
Alphas tend to cause double-strand breaks, and which are

662
00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:46.620
harder to repair and tend to be

663
00:39:46.660 --> 00:39:49.750
harder to resist. So alpha therapies can

664
00:39:50.380 --> 00:39:54.340
have better effects in radiation-resistant tumors, but also

665
00:39:54.440 --> 00:39:57.380
can have higher side effect profiles.

666
00:39:57.400 --> 00:40:01.159
And so some people like to favor alpha versus beta.

667
00:40:01.579 --> 00:40:05.350
I think both are going to have a role and betas have a good

668
00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:07.310
track record in clinical work,

669
00:40:08.320 --> 00:40:10.400
as do alphas with radium-223.

670
00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:13.140
In terms of theranostics in the U.S.,

671
00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:17.820
radioactive iodide's been around since the '40s, so nuclear medicine theranostics

672
00:40:17.860 --> 00:40:20.800
is not really new. We're just having a renaissance.

673
00:40:21.680 --> 00:40:24.260
MIBG is still available for imaging.

674
00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:27.860
The therapeutic I-131 version's not currently on the market,

675
00:40:28.700 --> 00:40:32.060
but that has been used for neuroendocrine tumors that secrete

676
00:40:32.080 --> 00:40:32.900
catecholamines.

677
00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:36.360
Skeletal scintigraphy has been used to select patients who are going to get

678
00:40:36.400 --> 00:40:40.160
radium-223 because radium-223 really binds to

679
00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:43.980
bone matrix that's turning over, as does the MDP in this bone

680
00:40:44.060 --> 00:40:44.400
scan.

681
00:40:45.260 --> 00:40:48.260
But in this talk, we're going to really focus on the newer agents, somatostatin

682
00:40:48.300 --> 00:40:51.940
receptor ligands, primarily for neuroendocrine tumors and PSMA

683
00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:55.720
ligands for prostate cancer, which have really changed the landscape of both

684
00:40:55.760 --> 00:40:58.140
diagnosis and treatment of these cancers.

685
00:40:59.880 --> 00:41:03.340
I do want to remind you though, when we say theranostics in nuclear medicine, we're

686
00:41:03.420 --> 00:41:06.860
often thinking, "Oh, there's a radiopharmaceutical therapy

687
00:41:06.920 --> 00:41:10.180
associated with a theranostic." And while I think that's the area that's getting

688
00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:14.120
the most excitement in the cancer field, appropriately so,

689
00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:17.570
there are potentials for theranostics through diagnostics.

690
00:41:18.020 --> 00:41:21.780
So estrogen receptor imaging with FES can

691
00:41:22.700 --> 00:41:26.480
tell you whether or not there's estrogen receptor present throughout the entire

692
00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:30.380
tumor burden, which at least in theory could influence decisions

693
00:41:30.420 --> 00:41:34.260
about hormonal therapies. And outside of cancer, actually amyloid

694
00:41:34.360 --> 00:41:36.620
PET is making a huge difference in

695
00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:40.920
the diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease as well as the treatment.

696
00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:43.400
So here's a patient with Alzheimer's disease.

697
00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:45.640
They have a lot of cortical amyloid.

698
00:41:45.720 --> 00:41:49.400
You can see that this cortical amyloid at the edge of the brain is decreased after

699
00:41:49.420 --> 00:41:52.080
therapy. And so there's also roles for

700
00:41:52.980 --> 00:41:56.570
theranostic nuclear medicine agents in cancer and other diseases that don't

701
00:41:56.580 --> 00:41:59.770
necessarily have a radiopharmaceutical therapy associated with

702
00:41:59.800 --> 00:42:03.590
them.In terms of molecular imaging for neuroendocrine tumors,

703
00:42:04.490 --> 00:42:08.190
somatostatin receptor ligands are really important for the theranostic

704
00:42:08.230 --> 00:42:12.170
piece. But I think something to consider in general in

705
00:42:12.190 --> 00:42:16.140
theranostics and imaging is that other agents can

706
00:42:16.190 --> 00:42:20.020
have a role. So FDG, the glucose analog that

707
00:42:20.030 --> 00:42:23.330
shows glucose metabolism, typically has low uptake in well-differentiated

708
00:42:23.340 --> 00:42:24.310
neuroendocrine tumors.

709
00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:28.750
But as neuroendocrine tumors dedifferentiate and become higher grade,

710
00:42:29.130 --> 00:42:32.619
they can often have more FDG uptake and actually lose their

711
00:42:32.670 --> 00:42:35.850
somatostatin receptor binding. So sometimes we use

712
00:42:35.930 --> 00:42:39.650
FDG to try to find disease that may be somatostatin

713
00:42:39.710 --> 00:42:43.500
receptor negative. And similarly for catecholamine-secreting tumors,

714
00:42:43.630 --> 00:42:47.490
MIBG still can play a role, and there's some investigational

715
00:42:47.530 --> 00:42:50.370
amino acids that may play a role in certain

716
00:42:50.730 --> 00:42:52.830
serotonin-secreting neuroendocrine tumors.

717
00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:57.590
So in terms of dotatate therapy today, the indications are

718
00:42:57.790 --> 00:43:01.640
Grade 1 or Grade 2, well-differentiated GEP-NETs,

719
00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:06.010
gastroenteropancreatic neuroendocrine tumors, who progressed

720
00:43:06.049 --> 00:43:09.030
on standard therapy, which is usually somatostatin analog.

721
00:43:09.750 --> 00:43:13.390
And more recently, first-line therapy, so the first treatment the patient

722
00:43:13.410 --> 00:43:17.270
receives for higher grade, Grade 2 and Grade 3, well-differentiated

723
00:43:17.310 --> 00:43:18.510
GEP-NETs.

724
00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:21.130
It is also the case that

725
00:43:21.990 --> 00:43:25.610
neuroendocrine tumors, uh, and other tumors that express

726
00:43:25.620 --> 00:43:29.390
somatostatin receptors like paragangliomas and meningiomas may also

727
00:43:29.430 --> 00:43:32.750
be good targets for somatostatin receptor-targeted

728
00:43:32.760 --> 00:43:36.630
theranostics. In terms of the toxicities that we think about when

729
00:43:36.670 --> 00:43:40.430
we treat patients clinically, for almost all radionuclide

730
00:43:40.440 --> 00:43:43.590
therapies, marrow toxicity is a major

731
00:43:43.630 --> 00:43:47.270
consideration. And then the biodistribution of the agent

732
00:43:47.370 --> 00:43:50.630
also influences organs that receive high doses.

733
00:43:50.650 --> 00:43:52.890
So kidneys, and to a lesser extent, liver,

734
00:43:53.690 --> 00:43:57.620
are organs we think about when we treat patients, and we follow them.

735
00:43:57.630 --> 00:44:01.610
And also, particularly for dotatate, but again, when we give

736
00:44:01.620 --> 00:44:05.370
therapeutic amounts of radiation, we also need to think about risk of future

737
00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:09.090
malignancy. And we'll come back to that a bit, but that's a long-term

738
00:44:09.130 --> 00:44:13.079
toxicity that I think we need to get a good handle on, particularly if

739
00:44:13.110 --> 00:44:16.870
we start thinking about using this earlier in the treatment of patients who may

740
00:44:16.930 --> 00:44:17.180
have

741
00:44:17.990 --> 00:44:19.310
decades of life ahead of them.

742
00:44:20.230 --> 00:44:21.970
And as with all of these

743
00:44:23.050 --> 00:44:23.510
current

744
00:44:24.830 --> 00:44:28.740
radiotheranostics, our goal is really to stop or slow the

745
00:44:28.790 --> 00:44:32.730
growth of tumor. Right now, we're not in a place where we can cure

746
00:44:32.790 --> 00:44:36.600
tumors with radiotheranostics, although hopefully in the future, I

747
00:44:36.650 --> 00:44:40.420
can tick this off. So in terms of practical aspects,

748
00:44:40.810 --> 00:44:44.470
our standard treatments are 200 millicuries or 7.4

749
00:44:44.570 --> 00:44:48.390
gigabequerels. To put that into perspective, that's about 20

750
00:44:48.470 --> 00:44:52.150
times the amount we might do for a PET scan with a shorter-lived

751
00:44:52.450 --> 00:44:55.330
PET-emitting radionuclide. For alpha therapies,

752
00:44:56.310 --> 00:45:00.240
particularly for longer-lived ones like radium or actinium, we're often giving

753
00:45:01.010 --> 00:45:04.859
microcuries, so a thousandfold less, and that reflects

754
00:45:04.859 --> 00:45:08.220
the higher biological potency of alphas versus betas.

755
00:45:08.850 --> 00:45:12.570
One of the things that makes dotatate therapy a little more challenging in terms of

756
00:45:12.610 --> 00:45:16.530
patient throughput is we need to give a co-infusion of

757
00:45:16.590 --> 00:45:20.490
arginine and lysine amino acids. That takes about four hours,

758
00:45:20.550 --> 00:45:22.730
and so patients are with us. They have to be monitored.

759
00:45:23.270 --> 00:45:26.210
Occasionally, they have difficulty with the infusion.

760
00:45:27.190 --> 00:45:31.150
But this really reduces the dose to the kidneys, and in the older

761
00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:34.870
literature, renal toxicity was a major issue with somatostatin receptor

762
00:45:34.910 --> 00:45:38.810
ligands like dotatate, but that's much, much less common now that we have this.

763
00:45:38.830 --> 00:45:41.290
But it does make the administration more complicated.

764
00:45:42.630 --> 00:45:46.440
If we see patients have hematologic toxicity or other toxicities,

765
00:45:46.830 --> 00:45:49.650
we can delay doses. We may reduce the future dose

766
00:45:50.650 --> 00:45:53.430
if the patient's able to recover from the toxicity.

767
00:45:55.170 --> 00:45:59.090
And patients get somatostatin analogs during the therapy, typically.

768
00:45:59.430 --> 00:46:03.030
We follow their lab values as well as their clinical status

769
00:46:03.810 --> 00:46:07.130
at each cycle and in between cycles.

770
00:46:07.190 --> 00:46:10.850
We expect to see some drop in blood counts with these therapies.

771
00:46:11.290 --> 00:46:15.190
As long as they don't fall below dangerous levels, typically, they will

772
00:46:15.310 --> 00:46:17.549
rebound and are eligible for their next cycle.

773
00:46:19.150 --> 00:46:22.990
In the case of dotatate therapy for typical GEP-NETs, we're

774
00:46:23.070 --> 00:46:24.960
usually imaging them at the end of therapy.

775
00:46:25.310 --> 00:46:28.750
There can be pseudoprogression from tumor swelling, so we don't usually image

776
00:46:28.790 --> 00:46:32.750
them during therapy, and neuroendocrine tumors that we treat

777
00:46:32.790 --> 00:46:36.730
with somatostatin receptor therapies tend to be relatively slow-growing.

778
00:46:37.410 --> 00:46:40.490
There are exceptions, but generally that's how this is done.

779
00:46:41.670 --> 00:46:44.650
Keyvon gave a nice preview for one of the pivotal trials, NETTER-1.

780
00:46:44.690 --> 00:46:48.200
This is really the one that got the Grade 1 and

781
00:46:48.350 --> 00:46:52.030
2 progression patient cohorts approved.

782
00:46:52.420 --> 00:46:56.410
And so you can see there's a very large progression-free survival benefit for those

783
00:46:56.450 --> 00:47:00.300
getting dotatate versus high-dose somatostatin analog in NETTER-1.

784
00:47:00.910 --> 00:47:03.060
In the interim analysis, there was a survival benefit.

785
00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:06.840
Actually following it out, that survival benefit wasn't

786
00:47:06.910 --> 00:47:10.630
seen in the final analysis. The common

787
00:47:10.670 --> 00:47:14.300
reason given, which I think is plausible, is there was a lot of crossover from

788
00:47:14.330 --> 00:47:18.160
control to dotatate therapy, and this was really

789
00:47:18.170 --> 00:47:21.330
designed for PFS, not OS, for that reason.

790
00:47:22.390 --> 00:47:26.290
More recently, the NETTER-2 trial showed that there

791
00:47:26.310 --> 00:47:29.940
was a progression-free survival benefit for those receiving

792
00:47:30.310 --> 00:47:33.890
dotatate therapy versus high-dose somatostatin

793
00:47:33.950 --> 00:47:34.510
analog

794
00:47:35.410 --> 00:47:38.430
in this higher grade, Grade 2 and 3, with KI

795
00:47:39.930 --> 00:47:43.810
67 scores up to 55%. And so now this is

796
00:47:43.890 --> 00:47:46.290
often a frontline treatment for these patients.

797
00:47:48.150 --> 00:47:51.290
In terms of switching gears to prostate cancer, there's many agents that have been

798
00:47:51.300 --> 00:47:54.530
developed. The two that are really most directly relevant to

799
00:47:54.570 --> 00:47:57.650
theranostics are PSMA ligands, which I'm going to talk about,

800
00:47:58.810 --> 00:48:02.730
some of which are approved, as well as bumetanide derivatives that

801
00:48:02.790 --> 00:48:06.730
target GRPR. These are quite interesting because there's

802
00:48:06.770 --> 00:48:10.750
differential expression of PSMA and GRPR in some tumors,

803
00:48:11.570 --> 00:48:15.370
and also GRPR ligands, at least the ones that are in

804
00:48:15.410 --> 00:48:19.170
advanced development, tend to undergo hepatobiliary excretion instead of

805
00:48:19.210 --> 00:48:23.194
renal excretion.If we think about prostate

806
00:48:23.274 --> 00:48:27.154
cancer from the time of diagnosis to progression

807
00:48:27.214 --> 00:48:28.734
and then advanced stages,

808
00:48:29.634 --> 00:48:31.714
imaging and more and more

809
00:48:32.854 --> 00:48:35.254
nuclear medicine therapies are playing a large role.

810
00:48:35.734 --> 00:48:35.834
So,

811
00:48:36.714 --> 00:48:40.294
when prostate cancer is initially diagnosed confined to the prostate

812
00:48:40.334 --> 00:48:44.294
gland, typically those patients will either undergo surgery or radiation

813
00:48:44.314 --> 00:48:47.234
therapy with or without androgen deprivation therapy.

814
00:48:47.264 --> 00:48:51.134
And many of those patients are cured, but frequently they will have a

815
00:48:51.154 --> 00:48:54.894
recurrence, often picked up with PSA before serum

816
00:48:54.914 --> 00:48:58.474
PSA, a blood test for prostate-specific antigen, which

817
00:48:58.994 --> 00:49:02.334
allows detection of recurrence, but it doesn't tell us

818
00:49:02.394 --> 00:49:05.974
where. And then these patients will typically be treated with androgen

819
00:49:06.014 --> 00:49:07.164
deprivation therapy,

820
00:49:08.274 --> 00:49:12.194
and will ultimately become resistant to those therapies and need either

821
00:49:12.274 --> 00:49:15.584
androgen receptor pathway inhibitors or taxane-based

822
00:49:15.674 --> 00:49:19.584
chemotherapy. And so in terms of imaging, active surveillance is

823
00:49:19.634 --> 00:49:20.494
often done with MR,

824
00:49:21.654 --> 00:49:25.604
and we are using PSMA PET for staging patients

825
00:49:25.634 --> 00:49:28.114
who have a more unfavorable

826
00:49:28.914 --> 00:49:32.084
risk factor for recurrence or metastases at the time of diagnosis.

827
00:49:32.954 --> 00:49:36.414
Another area where PSMA PET is frequently used is

828
00:49:36.434 --> 00:49:39.964
detecting and restaging patients who have biochemical recurrence,

829
00:49:40.634 --> 00:49:44.304
as well as now selecting patients for potential PSMA-based

830
00:49:44.374 --> 00:49:44.894
therapy.

831
00:49:45.714 --> 00:49:49.574
And so now currently, radiopharmaceutical therapy with PSMA ligands

832
00:49:49.934 --> 00:49:53.314
is confined to the more advanced castrate-resistant setting.

833
00:49:54.214 --> 00:49:57.804
But there are trials underway that are looking to shift this

834
00:49:57.854 --> 00:50:01.394
earlier. And already, as I'll come to in a moment, we've seen a shift

835
00:50:01.794 --> 00:50:04.534
to earlier phase treatment in prostate cancer.

836
00:50:05.134 --> 00:50:08.974
So the initial trial that was key to FDA approval was the

837
00:50:08.994 --> 00:50:12.534
VISION trial, that compared PSMA 617

838
00:50:13.294 --> 00:50:17.214
therapy to best standard of care, and both

839
00:50:17.274 --> 00:50:20.534
in terms of progression-free survival and overall survival,

840
00:50:21.654 --> 00:50:24.034
the PSMA therapy had

841
00:50:24.894 --> 00:50:26.514
a survival and progression benefit.

842
00:50:27.314 --> 00:50:29.554
There's also decreased skeletal events.

843
00:50:29.574 --> 00:50:33.374
The benefit was about a four-month median survival benefit, so not large, but

844
00:50:34.094 --> 00:50:37.974
typical of a lot of new therapies in very

845
00:50:38.054 --> 00:50:41.854
advanced cancer patients. And these are really patients who had no standard of

846
00:50:41.934 --> 00:50:45.774
care options. So even though four months isn't very long, it is a

847
00:50:45.814 --> 00:50:46.714
substantial

848
00:50:47.774 --> 00:50:48.234
change.

849
00:50:49.934 --> 00:50:53.734
More recently, the PSMA 4 trial compared PSMA

850
00:50:53.894 --> 00:50:57.654
617 to going to a second androgen

851
00:50:58.914 --> 00:51:02.574
receptor pathway inhibitor, and showed there was better progression-free

852
00:51:02.634 --> 00:51:05.294
survival, but very similar overall survival.

853
00:51:05.674 --> 00:51:09.334
So there wasn't a survival benefit in this group, but

854
00:51:09.694 --> 00:51:13.634
they are equivalent to switching ARPIs.

855
00:51:14.114 --> 00:51:17.694
And importantly, in our experience and in trials,

856
00:51:18.254 --> 00:51:21.954
generally this therapy is much easier for patients to tolerate

857
00:51:22.074 --> 00:51:25.254
than other therapies, including taxanes.

858
00:51:25.284 --> 00:51:29.264
And so often in patients who may have

859
00:51:30.234 --> 00:51:33.914
comorbidities or just not want to do taxane therapy, we

860
00:51:33.954 --> 00:51:37.614
may elect to do this over taxanes. But it's not that we have

861
00:51:38.614 --> 00:51:41.614
a definite survival benefit for them.

862
00:51:42.114 --> 00:51:43.814
So in terms of current indications,

863
00:51:44.714 --> 00:51:48.674
the metastatic castrate-resistant prostate cancer before or after

864
00:51:48.774 --> 00:51:52.644
taxane-based chemo. Again, hematologic toxicities

865
00:51:52.694 --> 00:51:56.374
are the main issue. Sometimes we see renal toxicity, and

866
00:51:56.854 --> 00:52:00.014
if you look at PSMA PET images, you see a lot of salivary gland

867
00:52:00.074 --> 00:52:02.734
activity. Many patients have dry mouth.

868
00:52:02.774 --> 00:52:06.644
With the beta emitters, that's generally been just symptomatic, but not

869
00:52:06.674 --> 00:52:10.054
really affecting the patient's overall quality of life.

870
00:52:11.014 --> 00:52:13.594
But they can be more severe with alpha emitters.

871
00:52:15.454 --> 00:52:19.114
In terms of standard treatment, 200 millicuries is a recurring theme

872
00:52:20.254 --> 00:52:23.974
currently. Hopefully, that will change as personalized dosimetry comes into play.

873
00:52:24.914 --> 00:52:27.794
And we're giving these every six weeks for six total cycles.

874
00:52:27.954 --> 00:52:31.154
Again, we can delay and reduce the dose if needed.

875
00:52:31.194 --> 00:52:34.704
We follow their labs. And interestingly, in terms of following

876
00:52:34.754 --> 00:52:38.254
response, we use serum PSA, which in most patients is a good

877
00:52:38.294 --> 00:52:42.093
marker. We use imaging, as well as the patient's overall

878
00:52:42.194 --> 00:52:46.054
symptoms and performance. So if patients come in with bone pain and it

879
00:52:46.134 --> 00:52:49.824
improves, that's actually an important piece of information suggesting they're

880
00:52:49.834 --> 00:52:53.574
responding. Many places are starting to do post-therapy

881
00:52:53.614 --> 00:52:56.134
imaging. This could theoretically be done for

882
00:52:56.934 --> 00:53:00.494
dosimetry, but also it can be done just as a way to

883
00:53:00.514 --> 00:53:04.494
follow therapy because lutetium-177 does emit imageable

884
00:53:04.574 --> 00:53:08.234
photons. And often patients will undergo an interim PET-CT,

885
00:53:08.934 --> 00:53:10.294
often after the third cycle,

886
00:53:11.094 --> 00:53:14.764
to see how they're doing. And this, unlike neuroendocrine tumors, kind of

887
00:53:14.794 --> 00:53:17.534
reflects the more aggressive, faster growth of

888
00:53:19.094 --> 00:53:22.114
prostate cancer in this setting than neuroendocrine tumors.

889
00:53:22.144 --> 00:53:25.814
So here's an example of a patient we treated with PSMA therapy.

890
00:53:25.854 --> 00:53:29.234
Here's their baseline PSMA PET-CT.

891
00:53:29.274 --> 00:53:32.314
Lots of disease with increased activity higher than liver.

892
00:53:32.674 --> 00:53:35.854
We didn't see any that was below liver that would make them ineligible.

893
00:53:36.434 --> 00:53:38.314
And here's their post-therapy imaging.

894
00:53:38.414 --> 00:53:40.694
And so you can see, this is just planar.

895
00:53:40.764 --> 00:53:44.694
We can also do spec CT for tomographic imaging, but for simplicity, showing you

896
00:53:44.714 --> 00:53:48.474
the planar. And you can see here's their PSA, and after three

897
00:53:48.594 --> 00:53:52.514
cycles, this patient had a pretty dramatic response, both in terms of their

898
00:53:52.894 --> 00:53:53.614
clinical

899
00:53:55.334 --> 00:53:58.974
presentation. They were having pain in this arm because of the bulky

900
00:53:59.154 --> 00:54:01.394
lymphadenopathy. You can see it's decreased.

901
00:54:01.444 --> 00:54:05.134
Their PSA dropped, and so this was a patient who's clearly having a good

902
00:54:05.194 --> 00:54:09.054
response. At the end of therapy, they look good except there's some

903
00:54:09.094 --> 00:54:13.064
increased activity in this supraclavicular node, which we saw previously,

904
00:54:13.114 --> 00:54:16.554
and their PSA is maybe bumped up a little.

905
00:54:16.654 --> 00:54:20.274
And so this is someone who might potentially benefit

906
00:54:20.394 --> 00:54:24.214
from a trial. Some people would advocate even

907
00:54:24.234 --> 00:54:27.754
external beam. The imaging is playing a role in

908
00:54:27.854 --> 00:54:28.254
also

909
00:54:29.294 --> 00:54:31.294
their next therapy if one's available.

910
00:54:31.854 --> 00:54:35.394
So some things to think about in terms of radiotheranostics for cancer.

911
00:54:35.834 --> 00:54:37.534
Obviously, the target is important.

912
00:54:37.634 --> 00:54:41.374
We need to be able to deliver our agent selectively or at least selectively

913
00:54:41.414 --> 00:54:45.154
enough to treat the cancer and spare normal tissues.

914
00:54:46.034 --> 00:54:48.614
We also need to think about the design of the radiopharmaceutical.

915
00:54:48.984 --> 00:54:52.434
And when I first got involved in nuclear medicine research, I mean, this was the

916
00:54:52.494 --> 00:54:54.774
area that really hooked me was you could

917
00:54:56.214 --> 00:54:59.998
go after almost any target.But there are

918
00:55:00.078 --> 00:55:03.198
other factors I'll talk about in a moment that I think are quite interesting.

919
00:55:03.258 --> 00:55:04.528
Obviously, you want to think about what

920
00:55:05.338 --> 00:55:08.488
type of cancer, what stage of cancer are you going after?

921
00:55:09.218 --> 00:55:13.158
And are you targeting the tumor or the microenvironment?

922
00:55:13.278 --> 00:55:16.338
So radium is an example of something that really isn't targeting the

923
00:55:16.378 --> 00:55:18.878
microenvironment. It's binding to mineralized bone.

924
00:55:18.918 --> 00:55:22.628
So we have clinically approved agents that are targeting the microenvironment, and

925
00:55:22.658 --> 00:55:26.598
some of the up-and-coming agents also are more microenvironment than tumor

926
00:55:26.678 --> 00:55:30.498
cells themselves. But beyond the target and the

927
00:55:30.598 --> 00:55:34.068
ligands, things like patient selection for

928
00:55:34.158 --> 00:55:37.998
therapy, as well as biomarkers that give prognosis are going to become

929
00:55:38.018 --> 00:55:41.678
increasingly important, especially if we're trying to give these agents

930
00:55:41.858 --> 00:55:44.918
earlier in treatment. We really want to pick the patients that are going to benefit

931
00:55:44.938 --> 00:55:48.658
the most, particularly if they have other treatment options.

932
00:55:49.308 --> 00:55:52.968
Pre- and post-therapy imaging and dosimetry, certainly already done

933
00:55:53.018 --> 00:55:56.558
for response assessment. There's a lot of interest in

934
00:55:56.578 --> 00:55:58.418
dosimetry and tailoring the dose

935
00:55:59.258 --> 00:56:01.418
to the patient to give the maximum safe dose.

936
00:56:02.638 --> 00:56:06.298
That has a lot of logistical challenges in practice, but

937
00:56:06.538 --> 00:56:09.378
it's an important area that is of great interest.

938
00:56:10.238 --> 00:56:13.448
Another thing is the amount, frequency, and duration of radiopharmaceutical

939
00:56:13.458 --> 00:56:16.978
therapy. I don't want to say the current regimens are arbitrary,

940
00:56:17.418 --> 00:56:21.218
but it could be that all patients may not need all

941
00:56:21.298 --> 00:56:23.678
six doses of PSMA therapy.

942
00:56:24.538 --> 00:56:26.338
The super responders may need fewer.

943
00:56:27.138 --> 00:56:28.918
There's also the potential to give the highest

944
00:56:30.458 --> 00:56:34.378
amount of activity on the first dose, because in the case of somatostatin receptor

945
00:56:34.398 --> 00:56:37.558
therapy, subsequent doses actually deliver less to the tumor.

946
00:56:37.608 --> 00:56:41.578
So there's a lot to be done in terms of optimizing these regimens.

947
00:56:41.638 --> 00:56:45.378
Oh, I've been talking about IV administration, but there's the potential to give

948
00:56:45.418 --> 00:56:49.278
these intra-arterially for meningiomas in the brain or for

949
00:56:49.818 --> 00:56:52.218
neuroendocrine tumors predominantly in the liver.

